Quick demo

Github: https://github.com/r9y9/pysinsy

[1]:

%pylab inline
import IPython
from IPython.display import Audio
import librosa
import librosa.display

Populating the interactive namespace from numpy and matplotlib

[2]:

import pysinsy

Synthesize audio

NOTE: The code here is for the demonstration purpose. It is highly recommended to customize configurations on your own.

[3]:

xml_path = "../../tests/song070_f00001_063.xml"

High-level API

[4]:

x, sr = pysinsy.synthesize(xml_path)

# Trim long silence part of the beginning
# NOTE: this is not generally needed
x = librosa.effects.trim(x, top_db=40)[0]

plt.figure(figsize=(16,4))
librosa.display.waveplot(x, sr, x_axis="time")
Audio(x, rate=sr)

[4]:

Using Sinsy API

[5]:

sinsy = pysinsy.Sinsy()
sinsy.setLanguages("j", pysinsy.get_default_dic_dir())
sinsy.loadScoreFromMusicXML(xml_path)
sinsy.loadVoices(pysinsy.get_default_htsvoice())

sinsy.setVolume(5.0)
x, sr = sinsy.synthesize()

x = librosa.effects.trim(x, top_db=40)[0]

plt.figure(figsize=(16,4))
librosa.display.waveplot(x, sr, x_axis="time")
Audio(x, rate=sr)

[5]:

[6]:

sinsy = pysinsy.Sinsy()
sinsy.setLanguages("j", pysinsy.get_default_dic_dir())
sinsy.loadScoreFromMusicXML(xml_path)
